definition.value: A dicarboxylic acid monoamide of succinic acid.
Any steroid based on a cholestane skeleton and its derivatives.
An acid or base which exhibits a colour change on neutralization by the basic or acidic titrant at or near the equivalence point of a titration.
Anything used in a scientific experiment that gives a visual change to indicate the presence of a substance or quality, change in a body, etc.
A substance which is adsorbed or desorbed with concomitant colour change at or near the equivalence point of a titration.
A colour indicator that is colourless on one side of the transition interval.
A colour indicator that possesses a different colour on each side of the transition interval.
A primary amine formally derived from ammonia by replacing one hydrogen atom by an aryl group.
Any carboxylic ester where the carboxylic acid component is butyric acid.
Any compound containing the thiocarbonyl group, C=S.
A pyridinium ion consisting of nicotinic acid having a methyl substituent on the pyridine nitrogen.
An aliphatic alcohol in which the aliphatic alkane chain is substituted by a hydroxy group at unspecified position.
An optically active form of 2-hydroxybutyric acid having (R)-configuration.
An optically active form of 2-hydroxybutyric acid having (S)-configuration.
The D isomer of N-acetylglucosamine.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2-methylbutan-1-ol.
An extracellular polysaccharide produced by Schizophyllum commune, consisting of a 1,3-beta-D-glucan backbone with 1,6-beta-D-glucosyl side chains.
A tetracycline analogue having a dimethylamino group at position 7 and lacking the methyl and hydroxy groups at position 5.
Monocyclic, bacterially produced or semisynthetic beta-lactam antibiotic. It lacks the double ring construction of the traditional beta-lactam antibiotics and can be easily synthesized.

A compound in which monosaccharide units are joined by glycosidic linkages. The term is commonly used to refer to a defined structure as opposed to a polymer of unspecified length or a homologous mixture. When the linkages are of other types the compounds are regarded as oligosaccharide analogues.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of 2-aminohexanoic acid having a methylthio substituent at the 6-position.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of 2-aminoheptanoic acid having a methylthio substituent at the 7-position.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of 2-aminooctanoic acid having a methylthio substituent at the 8-position.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of 2-aminononanoic acid having a methylthio substituent at the 9-position.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of 2-aminodecanoic acid having a methylthio substituent at the 10-position.
The 2,3-bis-O-(geranylgeranyl)- derivative of sn-glycerol 1-phosphate.
A salt of citric acid.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 3,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted by a decaprenyl group.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 5 are substituted by a methoxy and a decaprenyl group.
A carboxylic ester of pivalic acid.
A nanometre sized object.
A nanoparticle consisting of an iron oxide.
A nanoparticle consisting of magnetite.
